<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
Remarks
</p>
<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
The type material comprises a male, designated as the 
lectotype
, on which Noualhier (1897) based the original description, and two additional specimens, one female and the other of unknown sex. The last two were used to describe the colour and size of the body. The female is shorter (body length = 
7 mm
) than all the female specimens of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
studied (see 
<!--template match = tableCitation--><xref>Table 1</xref>
); it is more within the range of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. wollastoni</tp:taxon-name>
<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.
However, the vertex, deeply excavated, long, with the anterior margin angular, and the sharp carinae are more like the 
lectotype
of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
than the 
holotype
of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. wollastoni</tp:taxon-name>
<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.
The body size is larger than in 

<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. madeirensis</tp:taxon-name>
.

The original description of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
refers that the points along the tegmina veins are not setiferous, but the setae exist although they are difficult to recognize and easily breakable.
</p>
<!--template match = paragraph--><p>
The identification of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
has been difficult because no credible drawings of its genitalia were available. The original description did not provide any and those published later by Lindberg were wrongly attributed to this species. 
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref19283">Lindberg (1941: 27)</xref>
, despite having some doubts, identified specimens from the Azores as 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
. Later (
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref19369">Lindberg 1954: 4–5</xref>
), based on the same material and new specimens collected by Stora and Frey, he concluded that those of the Azores belonged to different species, which he described as 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. ( Sciocixius ) insularis</tp:taxon-name>
and 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. ( Ceratocixius ) azoricus</tp:taxon-name>
. In the same work, he provided the first illustrations of what he thought was the male genitalia of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
. However, the shape of the aedeagus resembles the genitalia of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. maderensis</tp:taxon-name>
(
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref19369">Lindberg 1954: 5</xref>
, figs 7–10), particularly the humped projection of the flagellum and the blunt tip of the apex of the aedeagus. The small spine is also comparatively long and curved. It seems that he wrongly illustrated the specimen(s) of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. madeirensis</tp:taxon-name>
from the Lundblad collection, which 
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref18564">
China
(1938)
</xref>
had previously studied and identified as 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
. In 1961, he studied these specimens again and new material that he had collected in Madeira. Here he provided new records that he assigned to 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. insularis</tp:taxon-name>
, and, again, what he believed to be the first drawings of the male genitalia of 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
(
<!--template match = bibRefCitation--><xref rid="ref18564">
China
1938: 54
</xref>
, fig. 
4g
–i) which are probably 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. wollastoni</tp:taxon-name>
<!--template match = taxonomicNameLabel-->sp. nov.
(see above). Since none of Lindberg’s drawings seem to correspond to 
<!--template match = taxonomicName--><tp:taxon-name>C. verticalis</tp:taxon-name>
, the genital structures of this species are illustrated here for the first time.
</p>
